   =20
      Credit Suisse
   =20
 =20
One way to tell the story of Credit Suisse Group AG and Archegos Capital Ma=
nagement is that Archegos was a big hedge fund, Credit Suisse loaned it a l=
ot of money to buy stocks, the stocks went down, Archegos didn=E2=80=99t pa=
y back the money, Credit Suisse lost billions of dollars, and in penance it=
 is shutting down its business of lending money to hedge funds and instead =
shifting its focus to helping rich people manage their money. That version =
of the story is almost true. Bloomberg News  reports today:Credit Suisse Gr=
oup AG will exit the hedge fund business at the heart of the Archegos Capit=
al Management scandal and shift more resources to wealth management as it s=
eeks to draw a line under a tumultuous year.The bank is discontinuing most =
prime brokerage after the implosion of Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s family office c=
ost it billions of dollars and is moving about $3 billion of capital from t=
he investment bank to the private bank. The Swiss lender is also simplifyin=
g its structure into four divisions, including a single unit that groups to=
gether its wealth management businesses, as reported earlier this week by B=
loomberg.=C2=A0Chairman Antonio Horta-Osorio has spent the past six months =
conducting a root-and-branch review of Credit Suisse after disastrous risk =
lapses wiped out billions in profit, plunged the bank into crisis and led t=
o an overhaul of top management. He stopped short of the radical changes th=
at characterised Deutsche Bank AG=E2=80=99s overhaul three years ago, elect=
ing to pare back areas that backfired while investing in the more stable bu=
sinesses of helping the world=E2=80=99s wealthy manage their fortunes.=C2=
=A0But my first sentence=C2=A0is not quite=C2=A0true. There is one small in=
accuracy, which is that Archegos was not actually a big hedge fund.[3] Func=
tionally, it was a big hedge fund: It was big ($20 billion of assets at its=
 peak), it was run by a former =E2=80=9CTiger Cub=E2=80=9D hedge fund manag=
er (Hwang), and its relationship with Credit Suisse was through the prime b=
rokerage division that finances hedge funds. But=C2=A0actually=C2=A0it was =
a big family office. It was not a hedge fund; it did not manage money for o=
utside clients. It managed Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s fortune.=C2=A0A family offi=
ce, particularly at that scale, is not=C2=A0quite=C2=A0the same thing as a =
rich person=E2=80=99s personal brokerage account; Archegos had well-paid pr=
ofessional employees (with, presumably, some of their own money invested in=
 Archegos) and its own legal entity and so forth. But it is=C2=A0kind of=C2=
=A0like a rich person=E2=80=99s personal brokerage account, in that Hwang c=
alled the shots,=C2=A0answered to no one but himself, and managed the money=
 basically to fund his own lifestyle and philanthropy. Presumably Credit Su=
isse=E2=80=99s very best wealth managers, its top experts at =E2=80=9Chelpi=
ng the world=E2=80=99s wealthy manage their fortunes,=E2=80=9D had relation=
ships with billionaires who were not so=C2=A0different from Hwang in terms =
of wealth or financial sophistication or risk appetite or the trades they w=
ere doing. They just came in through the =E2=80=9Cwealth management=E2=80=
=9D door rather than the =E2=80=9Cprime brokerage=E2=80=9D door.[4]We have =
 talked in detail about the failures of risk management that led Credit Sui=
sse to lose $5.5 billion lending money to Bill Hwang. They were essentially=
 not=C2=A0intellectual=C2=A0failures but social=C2=A0failures. Credit Suiss=
e did not fail to understand the risk of its loans. It understood the risks=
 perfectly, knew that it needed more collateral, but dragged its feet in as=
king for that collateral and, when it did ask, allowed Archegos to drag=C2=
=A0its=C2=A0feet in responding. That is in some sense just how banks behave=
 sometimes with big lucrative clients: =E2=80=9CIf we don=E2=80=99t get thi=
s collateral we might lose billions on a catastrophic collapse=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0sounds=C2=A0bad when I type it here, but when stocks are going up it fee=
ls somewhat abstract to the relationship manager, whereas =E2=80=9Cif I cal=
l the client and ask for more collateral he will be annoyed and say cutting=
 things and our five-minute conversation will be painfully awkward=C2=A0and=
 then=C2=A0I=E2=80=99ll feel bad all afternoon=E2=80=9D feels very real and=
 immediate. Plus the client might say no and take his business elsewhere! T=
hen the relationship manager might get fired! Exactly as fired as she=E2=80=
=99d be if the bank lost billions on a catastrophic collapse! Incentives!I =
suppose you can wonder: If instead of showing up at the door of Credit Suis=
se=E2=80=99s prime brokerage division with a  $200 million family office=C2=
=A0that he eventually grew to $20 billion, Hwang had shown up at the door o=
f Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s private bank with a $200 million family fortune a=
nd asked for some help growing it to $20 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0help like, =
say, getting leverage on single-stock bets through total return swaps =E2=
=80=94 what would have been different? Would Credit Suisse have said =E2=80=
=9Cno, we don=E2=80=99t do that kind of leverage for our private wealth cus=
tomers, but can we interest you in  some Greensill notes?=E2=80=9D Would it=
 have given Hwang some leverage but, as his positions grew into the billion=
s, would it have said =E2=80=9Chey this is our biggest and most levered pri=
vate wealth client, let=E2=80=99s dial that back a bit=E2=80=9D? Whereas he=
 went strangely unnoticed in the hedge fund business?=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t =
know the answer. My general impression is that=C2=A0banks=C2=A0have more to=
ols to deal strictly with private wealth clients than with big hedge funds:=
 Hedge funds often deal with banks on terms of rough equality, demanding tw=
o-way collateral posting and objective marks and so forth, while private we=
alth clients are sort of fancy retail clients who are more subject to the b=
ank=E2=80=99s risk-management whims. On the other hand my impression is tha=
t=C2=A0bankers=C2=A0who deal with private wealth clients are mostly in the =
business of getting more business, and lean into, like, wining and dining a=
nd flattering and pitching their clients, while the traders and prime broke=
rs who deal with hedge funds are usually a bit more in the business of risk=
 management and think more about protecting themselves from their customers=
. So in general it could go either way, though in Hwang=E2=80=99s particula=
r case it is hard to see how private wealth could have been more obsequious=
 than prime brokerage was. It could have had lower leverage limits though.A=
nyway I guess the point is that it is tempting to say =E2=80=9CCredit Suiss=
e=E2=80=99s lending-to-hedge-funds business lost a zillion dollars so it is=
 shutting that down and focusing on the business of helping rich people get=
 richer.=E2=80=9D But those businesses are not so different from each other=
!
 =20
   =20
      Banking culture
   =20
 =20
Would you say that right now is a boom time for investment banks? I am not =
sure. Statistically it seems like the answer is yes. The big banks are  as =
profitable as they have ever been. The New York securities industry=C2=A0bo=
nus pool=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0a decent proxy for Wall Street pay =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0for 2020 was the third-highest ever, behind only 2006 and 2007, which=
 were indisputably boomy years. Also people are busy. Mergers and underwrit=
ings and SPAC deals are all active; activity leads to money.And yet. Anecdo=
tally, when I talk to my friends who are still in banking, they=C2=A0compla=
in that the compensation and the sense of fun aren=E2=80=99t what they used=
 to be. Arguably all bankers have said that forever, but it does seem like,=
 on a=C2=A0relative=C2=A0basis, investment banks do not have the swagger th=
at they had in 2006 and 2007. Post-crisis reforms have turned the big inves=
tment banks into regulated bank holding companies and moved some of the mos=
t swaggery businesses out of the banks; you can=E2=80=99t really run a priv=
ate equity fund or a prop trading desk at a bank anymore.Meanwhile the big =
tech companies have taken over the banks=E2=80=99 prominent cultural positi=
on of, like, =E2=80=9Crich and evil.=E2=80=9D I worked at Goldman Sachs Gro=
up Inc. from 2007 to 2011, and I do think that part of the appeal at the ti=
me was that everyone hated us.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CA great vampire squid wrapped =
around the face of humanity, relentlessly jamming its blood funnel into any=
thing that smells like money=E2=80=9D is, in its way, kind of flattering! N=
ow that=E2=80=99s just Facebook though. (Sorry, Meta Platforms Inc.) People=
 might still hate Goldman when they think about it, but mostly they don=E2=
=80=99t.Also the crypto industry is now the leading place to make quick ine=
xplicable fortunes from financial innovation. Also=C2=A0Goldman Sachs is do=
ing consumer banking and retail robo-advising. It=E2=80=99s all fine, just =
fine, these are public companies managing to a solid return on equity for t=
heir shareholders. They used to be something else though.On the other hand =
this is some absolute boom-time behavior:When one Citi analyst informed a s=
uperior by email that he=E2=80=99d caught COVID and was heading to the hosp=
ital, the VP replied and gave him a new assignment. =E2=80=9CNo time off. H=
e was like, =E2=80=98Oh, thanks for letting me know. I actually have a staf=
fing for you.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9DI have heard stories like that before, but t=
hose were 2007 stories. Those were stories of =E2=80=9Cmoney was pouring do=
wn on us in torrents and we needed every available person to grab a bucket =
and collect it.=E2=80=9D Those were stories of seniors saying to juniors, l=
ook, I love money, and you love money, and there is so much money, you gott=
a get=C2=A0some money in the hospital. Obviously the juniors were not happy=
 about it! Because it is terrible. But it was in a sense the bargain they h=
ad made. Later they would be handed a pile of money and feel pleased.That a=
necdote is from this Jen Wieczner story in Intelligencer about the complain=
ts of junior investment bankers, at Goldman and Citi and elsewhere, over th=
e last year or so. The best-known of these complaints was the Goldman Power=
Point in which junior analysts complained that they were being abused; one =
said =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve been through foster care and this is arguably wo=
rse.=E2=80=9D Wieczner reports on the reaction:In the middle and higher ech=
elons of Goldman, the analysts=E2=80=99 plight received little sympathy. Ra=
ndy Habeeb was working as a trader in the bank=E2=80=99s New York office wh=
en the PowerPoint leaked. =E2=80=9CTo be honest with you, I was actually re=
ally pissed,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s kind of like an unw=
ritten code that you just don=E2=80=99t talk about it. You kind of just man=
 up and do it.=E2=80=9D He=E2=80=99s since left Goldman to start his own fi=
rm, Habeeb Capital, where he sits in front of a faux-grass wall and keeps o=
n his desk a mug with the words =E2=80=9CF***er in Charge of You F***ing F*=
**s.=E2=80=9D Even the survey=E2=80=99s most disturbing allegations failed =
to resonate with longtime bankers. =E2=80=9CI haven=E2=80=99t been in foste=
r care,=E2=80=9D said a former Goldman executive, who started as an analyst=
. =E2=80=9CBut that struck me as somewhat dramatic. Either highly dramatic,=
 or they had a great foster-care experience!=E2=80=9DWell. Look. That's mea=
n. But if it=E2=80=99s like =E2=80=9Cthis is the unavoidable price of admis=
sion to an elite club of vast wealth and influence=E2=80=9D then you can ki=
nd of see where they=E2=80=99re coming from. But Habeeb left! The club is j=
ust, meh, whatever. Wieczner writes:This year=E2=80=99s raises brought the =
starting salary for investment bankers to at least $100,000, not including =
annual bonuses, which often double their total compensation.And yet it=E2=
=80=99s not at all clear that the extra lucre has restored equilibrium to t=
he investment-banking bargain =E2=80=94 a job that has always sucked and al=
ways paid well enough to convince hordes of Ivy Leaguers to apply anyway. O=
n top of salary and bonus, analyst posts have traditionally offered a chanc=
e to see how Wall Street operates up close before providing off-ramps to sw=
eet gigs in hedge funds and private equity. Today, all three of these major=
 perks are less compelling than they were just a few years ago. Tech pays b=
etter; the pandemic has deprived analysts of observing much of anything; an=
d banking experience is not remotely a prerequisite to enter the hottest se=
ctors in finance, namely venture capital and crypto.For many new investment=
 bankers, the deal they struck for their first two years out of college is =
looking like an increasingly out-of-the-money trade.What if investment bank=
ing has become not a golden ticket but a normal job, except it=E2=80=99s a =
normal job with 120-hour weeks and a culture of weird macho hazing? That se=
ems bad.
