om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Credit Suisse</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to tell the story of Credit Su=
isse Group AG and Archegos Capital Management is that Archegos was a big he=
dge fund, Credit Suisse loaned it a lot of money to buy stocks, the stocks =
went down, Archegos didn=E2=80=99t pay back the money, Credit Suisse lost b=
illions of dollars, and in penance it is shutting down its business of lend=
ing money to hedge funds and instead shifting its focus to helping rich peo=
ple manage their money. That version of the story is almost true. Bloomberg=
 News <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25582014.262=
653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMDQvY3J=
lZGl0LXN1aXNzZS10by1zaHJpbmstaW52ZXN0bWVudC1iYW5rLWluLXdlYWx0aC1sZWQtb3Zlcm=
hhdWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwNDIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291c=
mNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMTA0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd4de287f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> reports today</a>:</p><blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse Group AG will exit the hedge fun=
d business at the heart of the Archegos Capital Management scandal and shif=
t more resources to wealth management as it seeks to draw a line under a tu=
multuous year.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank is discontinuing mo=
st prime brokerage after the implosion of Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s family offic=
e cost it billions of dollars and is moving about $3 billion of capital fro=
m the investment bank to the private bank. The Swiss lender is also simplif=
ying its structure into four divisions, including a single unit that groups=
 together its wealth management businesses, as reported earlier this week b=
y Bloomberg.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Chairman Antonio Horta-O=
sorio has spent the past six months conducting a root-and-branch review of =
Credit Suisse after disastrous risk lapses wiped out billions in profit, pl=
unged the bank into crisis and led to an overhaul of top management. He sto=
pped short of the radical changes that characterised Deutsche Bank AG=E2=80=
=99s overhaul three years ago, electing to pare back areas that backfired w=
hile investing in the more stable businesses of helping the world=E2=80=99s=
 wealthy manage their fortunes.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">But my first sentence=C2=A0is not <em>quite=C2=A0</em>true. There i=
s one small inaccuracy, which is that Archegos was not actually a big hedge=
 fund.[3] Functionally, it was a big hedge fund: It was big (<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25582014.262653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMDgvaG93LWJpbGwtaHdhbmctb2Y=
tYXJjaGVnb3MtY2FwaXRhbC1sb3N0LTIwLWJpbGxpb24taW4tdHdvLWRheXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMT=
EwNDIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImd=
XRtX3Rlcm09MjExMTA0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBe68da53e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">$20 billion of assets</a> at its peak), it was run by a=
 former =E2=80=9CTiger Cub=E2=80=9D hedge fund manager (Hwang), and its rel=
ationship with Credit Suisse was through the prime brokerage division that =
finances hedge funds. But=C2=A0<em>actually=C2=A0</em>it was a big family o=
ffice. It was not a hedge fund; it did not manage money for outside clients=
. It managed Bill Hwang=E2=80=99s fortune.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">A family office, particularly at that scale, is not=C2=A0<em>quite=C2=
=A0</em>the same thing as a rich person=E2=80=99s personal brokerage accoun=
t; Archegos had well-paid professional employees (with, presumably, some of=
 their own money invested in Archegos) and its own legal entity and so fort=
h. But it is=C2=A0<em>kind of=C2=A0</em>like a rich person=E2=80=99s person=
al brokerage account, in that Hwang called the shots,=C2=A0answered to no o=
ne but himself, and managed the money basically to fund his own lifestyle a=
nd philanthropy. Presumably Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s very best wealth manage=
rs, its top experts at =E2=80=9Chelping the world=E2=80=99s wealthy manage =
their fortunes,=E2=80=9D had relationships with billionaires who were not <=
em>so=C2=A0</em>different from Hwang in terms of wealth or financial sophis=
tication or risk appetite or the trades they were doing. They just came in =
through the =E2=80=9Cwealth management=E2=80=9D door rather than the =E2=80=
=9Cprime brokerage=E2=80=9D door.[4]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We hav=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25582014.262653/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjkvYXJ=
jaGVnb3Mtd2FzLXRvby1idXN5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEwNDIxX01PTk=
VZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09M=
jExMTA0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5782dcef" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> talked in detail</a> about the failures of risk management that le=
d Credit Suisse to lose $5.5 billion lending money to Bill Hwang. They were=
 essentially not=C2=A0<em>intellectual=C2=A0</em>failures but <em>social=C2=
=A0</em>failures. Credit Suisse did not fail to understand the risk of its =
loans. It understood the risks perfectly, knew that it needed more collater=
al, but dragged its feet in asking for that collateral and, when it did ask=
, allowed Archegos to drag=C2=A0<em>its=C2=A0</em>feet in responding. That =
is in some sense just how banks behave sometimes with big lucrative clients=
: =E2=80=9CIf we don=E2=80=99t get this collateral we might lose billions o=
n a catastrophic collapse=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>sounds=C2=A0</em>bad when I typ=
e it here, but when stocks are going up it feels somewhat abstract to the r=
elationship manager, whereas =E2=80=9Cif I call the client and ask for more=
 collateral he will be annoyed and say cutting things and our five-minute c=
onversation will be painfully awkward=C2=A0and then=C2=A0I=E2=80=99ll feel =
bad all afternoon=E2=80=9D feels very real and immediate. Plus the client m=
ight say no and take his business elsewhere! Then the relationship manager =
might get fired! Exactly as fired as she=E2=80=99d be if the bank lost bill=
ions on a catastrophic collapse! Incentives!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">I suppose you can wonder: If instead of showing up at the door of Credit =
Suisse=E2=80=99s prime brokerage division with a <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25582014.262653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMDIvZ29kLWFuZC1tYW4tY29sbGlkZS1pbi1iaWx=
sLWh3YW5nLXMtZHVlbGluZy1saXZlcy1vbi13YWxsLXN0cmVldD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTA0MjFfTU=
9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVyb=
T0yMTExMDQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB576fb48=
7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> $200 million family office</a>=C2=A0that he eventually grew t=
o $20 billion, Hwang had shown up at the door of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s pr=
ivate bank with a $200 million family fortune and asked for some help growi=
ng it to $20 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0help like, say, getting leverage on sin=
gle-stock bets through total return swaps =E2=80=94 what would have been di=
fferent? Would Credit Suisse have said =E2=80=9Cno, we don=E2=80=99t do tha=
t kind of leverage for our private wealth customers, but can we interest yo=
u in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25582014.2626=
53/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMDYvY3Jl=
ZGl0LXN1aXNzZS1tYXktbGV0LWZ1bmQtY2xpZW50cy10YWtlLWhpdC1vbi1ncmVlbnNpbGwtbG9=
zc2VzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMDQyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdX=
JjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTEwNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4725540d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> some Greensill notes</a>?=E2=80=
=9D Would it have given Hwang some leverage but, as his positions grew into=
 the billions, would it have said =E2=80=9Chey this is our biggest and most=
 levered private wealth client, let=E2=80=99s dial that back a bit=E2=80=9D=
? Whereas he went strangely unnoticed in the hedge fund business?=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know the answer. My general im=
pression is that=C2=A0<em>banks=C2=A0</em>have more tools to deal strictly =
with private wealth clients than with big hedge funds: Hedge funds often de=
al with banks on terms of rough equality, demanding two-way collateral post=
ing and objective marks and so forth, while private wealth clients are sort=
 of fancy retail clients who are more subject to the bank=E2=80=99s risk-ma=
nagement whims. On the other hand my impression is that=C2=A0<em>bankers=C2=
=A0</em>who deal with private wealth clients are mostly in the business of =
getting more business, and lean into, like, wining and dining and flatterin=
g and pitching their clients, while the traders and prime brokers who deal =
with hedge funds are usually a bit more in the business of risk management =
and think more about protecting themselves from their customers. So in gene=
ral it could go either way, though in Hwang=E2=80=99s particular case it is=
 hard to see how private wealth could have been more obsequious than prime =
brokerage was. It could have had lower leverage limits though.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway I guess the point is that it is tempting to say=
 =E2=80=9CCredit Suisse=E2=80=99s lending-to-hedge-funds business lost a zi=
llion dollars so it is shutting that down and focusing on the business of h=
elping rich people get richer.=E2=80=9D But those businesses are not so dif=
ferent from each other!</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D=
"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
